## 1. Foundations & Terminology

| Term | Definition |
|---|---|
| **Asset** | Anything of value to the organization (data, system, service, reputation) |
| **Vulnerability** | A weakness that could be exploited |
| **Threat** | Anything capable of exploiting a vulnerability (actor, event, or circumstance) |
| **Risk** | The likelihood x impact of a threat exploiting a vulnerability against an asset |
| **Exploit** | Code or technique that takes advantage of a vulnerability |
| **Attack surface** | The sum of all points where an attacker could try to enter or extract data |
| **Attack vector** | The specific path/method used to gain access |
| **Zero-day** | A vulnerability unknown to the vendor with no patch available |
| **PoC (Proof of Concept)** | Demonstration code/evidence that a vulnerability is genuinely exploitable |
| **IOC (Indicator of Compromise)** | Forensic evidence suggesting a breach has occurred |
| **TTPs** | Tactics, Techniques, and Procedures — how adversaries operate (core to MITRE ATT&CK) |

### VA vs PT vs Red Team vs Purple Team

| Engagement Type | Goal | Depth | Exploitation? | Announced to Blue Team? |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Vulnerability Assessment (VA) | Identify and rank as many weaknesses as possible | Broad, shallow | No (or minimal, safe validation only) | Yes |
| Penetration Test (PT) | Prove real-world impact of specific vulnerabilities | Narrower, deeper | Yes, controlled | Yes |
| Red Team | Emulate a real adversary's full attack chain, test detection & response | Narrow, very deep, goal-oriented | Yes, full chain | Usually no (tests SOC) |
| Purple Team | Collaborative exercise to improve detection controls in real time | Focused on specific TTPs | Yes, but transparent | Yes, explicitly collaborative |
| Bug Bounty | Continuous, crowd-sourced vulnerability discovery | Varies by researcher | Varies by program rules | N/A (ongoing program) |

**Interview-grade one-liner:** "VA answers 'what's wrong,' PT answers 'can it actually be exploited and what's the impact,' Red Team answers 'would we even notice.'"

