## 8. Exploitation — Network & Infrastructure

- **Unpatched service exploitation** — matching enumerated service versions to public CVEs/exploit-db entries.
- **Default/weak credentials** — still one of the most common initial access vectors in real engagements; test default creds on network devices, admin panels, databases.
- **Password attacks:**
  - Brute force / credential stuffing (`Hydra`, `Medusa` for online; `Hashcat`, `John the Ripper` for offline hash cracking).
  - Password spraying — trying one or a few common passwords across *many* accounts (avoids account lockout thresholds that brute-forcing a single account would trigger).
- **Man-in-the-middle / network-level attacks:** ARP spoofing, LLMNR/NBT-NS poisoning (`Responder` — captures hashes when Windows hosts broadcast name resolution requests that don't get a legitimate response).
- **Firewall/IDS evasion (conceptual, know for discussion, not for irresponsible use):** fragmentation, timing (slow scans), decoy scanning, source port manipulation — important to be able to discuss *why* these exist and how blue teams detect them, since your Fortinet/Sophos background gives you the defensive counterpart to this.

